# Detect Lane Lines in a Grayscale Image

msg.data: Detect Lane Lines in a Grayscale Image

paragraphs.text:
%python
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import cv2

%md
### Read Image and Display It

Matplotlib **[imread()](https://matplotlib.org/api/image_api.html)** reads an image from a file into an numpy array **image_color = mpimg.imread('filepath')**. OpenCV **[cvtColor()](https://docs.opencv.org/3.2.0/df/d9d/tutorial_py_colorspaces.html)** converts an image from one color space to another and stores it into a numpy array **image_gray = cv2.cvtColor(image_color, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)**. Numpy **[shape](https://docs.opencv.org/3.0-beta/doc/py_tutorials/py_core/py_basic_ops/py_basic_ops.html)** returns a tuple for number of rows, columns and _channels (if colored image is true)_. Matplotlib **[imshow()](https://matplotlib.org/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.imshow.html)** displays an image **plt.imshow(image_gray, cmap = 'gray')**. Zeppelin **[show()](https://github.com/brigade/incubator-zeppelin/blob/master/spark/src/main/java/org/apache/zeppelin/spark/ZeppelinContext.java)** is used to show Matplotlib, graphs in the notebook **z.show(plt)**.

paragraphs.text:
%python
# matplotlib imread() reads a colored image from a specified file into an numpy.array
image_color = mpimg.imread('/home/self-car/Autonomous-Car/application/lib/self-driving-cars/computer-vision/image_lane_c.jpg')
# opencv cvtColor() converts an image from BGR color space to Grayscale
image_gray = cv2.cvtColor(image_color, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
# numpy shape() returns number of rows and columns for the grayscaled image
image_gray.shape

%python
plt.imshow(image_gray, cmap = 'gray') # display an image
z.show(plt) # needed for Zeppelin Python Interpreter to display matplotlib graph

%md
### Mask Non White Colored Pixels in the Image

Expose the white pixels from the image and **image mask** all other non white pixels to detect lane lines. Numpy **[copy()](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.copy.html)** copies the array of the gray image into numpy array **image_copy = np.copy(image_gray)**. All pixels from beginning to end of the numpy array are observed at every _(row, column)_ via **[image_copy[:,:]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16815928/what-does-mean-on-numpy-arrays)** and every colored pixel is checked for non pure white via **< 250** _(pixels less than range 250 to 255)_ and if true, then that pixel is changed to black by way of **image_copy[ (image_copy[:,:] < 250) ] = 0**. Matplotlib **[imshow()](https://matplotlib.org/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.imshow.html)** displays our image with the detected lane lines **plt.imshow(image_copy, cmap = 'gray')** and Zeppelin **[show()](https://github.com/brigade/incubator-zeppelin/blob/master/spark/src/main/java/org/apache/zeppelin/spark/ZeppelinContext.java)** shows the Matplotlib graph in the notebook **z.show(plt)**.
